=====Intransitive=====
#To [[end up]] in two or more [[piece]]s, which can't easily be [[reassembled]].
#: ''The vase fell to the floor and '''broke''' into a thousand pieces.''
#(''medicine'') Of a [[bone]], to [[crack]] or [[fracture]] through a [[sudden]] [[physical]] [[strain]], such as a [[collision]].
#:''My shin bone '''broke''' when I fell down stairs last week.''
#To [[stop]] [[function]]ing [[properly]] or [[altogether]].
#:''The fridge has '''broken'''.''
#To [[interrupt]] or [[cease]] one's [[work]] or [[occupation]] [[temporarily]].
#:''Let's '''break''' for lunch.''
<!--I'm not quite sure about this one. Anyone who plays tennis?
#(''tennis'') To win a game as [[receiver]] or receivers (in case of a [[double]])-->
#(''billiards'') To make the [[first]] [[shot]].
#:''Is it your or my turn to '''break'''?''

======Synonyms======
*(''end up in two or more pieces''): [[burst]], [[bust]], [[shatter]], [[shear]], [[smash]], [[split]]
*(''of a bone''): [[crack]], [[fracture]]
*(''stop functioning''): [[break down]], [[bust]], [[fail]], [[go down]] (''of a computer or computer network'')
*(''interrupt''): [[interrupt]], [[pause]]

======Antonyms======
*(''interrupt''): [[carry on]], [[continue]], [[go on]], [[restart]], [[resume]]

