=====Transitive=====
#To [[cause]] to [[end up]] in two or more [[piece]]s.
#: ''He '''broke''' the vase.''
#(''medicine'') Of a bone, to cause to [[crack]] under [[physical]] [[strain]].
#:''He killed him by '''breaking''' his neck.''
#(''medicine'') Of a bone, to [[fracture]] accidentially.
#:''I broke my arm and now I have it in plaster.''
#To cause to [[malfunction]] or [[stop]] [[work]]ing altogether.
#:''Did you two '''break''' the trolley by racing with it?''
#To cause a person or animal to [[lose]] his/her/its [[will]], usually obtained by means of [[torture]].
#:''You have to '''break''' an elephant before you can use it as an animal of burden.''
#:'''''Breaking''' a man will make him obedient.''
#To do that which is [[forbid]]den by (a rule or rules).
#:''Stealing is breaking the law.''
#(''gaming slang'') To [[design]] or make (a [[legal]] but [[unfair]] [[move]]).
#: ''Letting white have three extra queens would '''break''' chess.''

======Synonyms======
*(''cause to end up in two or more pieces''): [[shatter]], [[smash]]
*(''of a bone, intentionally''): [[crack]], [[fracture]]
*(''of a bone, accidentially''): [[crack]], [[fracture]]
*(''cause to malfunction or stop working altogether''): [[bust]]
*(''cause a person or animal to lose his/her/its will''): [[subject]], [[tame]]
*(''do that which is forbidden by''): [[contravene]], [[go against]], [[violate]]

======Antonyms======
*(''cause to end up in two or more pieces''): [[assemble]], [[join]], [[mend]], [[put together]], [[repair]]

